        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator setup: following our science case, we will make use of the single continuum mode in Band 6, which implies a total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz, with 31.25 MHz width channels. This is the correlator set-up that requires the shortest observing time to reach our science goal. 

Sensitivity: we request 1-sigma rms sensitivity of 0.025 mJy. This sensitivity will allow us to reach a 3-sigma dust mass sensitivity of 0.5 Mearth, which brings us close to the debris disk regime.

Antenna setup: because of the distance to NNSer we do not expect to resolve the potential circumbinary disk around NN Ser. As we are only interested in detecting the continuum emission, we request these observations to be carried out in a compact configuration (C34-1, C34-2, or C34-3). This will assure enough measurements at the shortest baselines, optimizing the total flux measurement. Given the object declination (12 deg) we do not expect shadowing to be a problem, even for the most compact configuration.

Based on the ALMA OT calculator, the requested sensitivity translates into a total of 1.16 hours of ALMA time, including calibrations and overheads.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
