    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The recent frequent detection of giant planets around detached post-common envelope binaries (PCEBs) may significantly influence our understanding of planet formation. These circumbinary planets have likely formed from the expelled material following the common envelope evolution of the host binary system. Such a second generation scenario, if confirmed, could provide crucial constraints on planet formation theories. An ideal test-bed for the hypothesis of second generation planet formation is the PCEB NNSer with its two circumbinary giant planets. The common envelope evolution of NNSer occurred only a million years ago thus any second generation protoplanetary disk will still be detectable with ALMA. We therefore here request 1.16 hrs in band-6 to ultimately test the second generation planet formation scenario.</prp:abstract>
